[9/30, 11:13 AM] Janani: POP3 vs. IMAP vs. SMTP
POP3, IMAP and SMTP are all email protocols. The three protocols differ in a variety of ways, including:
POP3 and IMAP are protocols for retrieving emails from a server, while SMTP is for transmitting emails.
POP3 downloads messages directly to your device. In comparison, IMAP retains the message on the server.
POP3 frees up storage space on servers, but IMAP frees up space on local hard drives.
While IMAP synchronizes email content across devices, POP3 keeps separate settings and email content on different devices.
IMAP can be identically useful for multiple devices, while POP3 is more suitable for use on a single device because of its synchronization inability.
POP3 retrieves only the emails within your inbox folder. In contrast, IMAP retrieves content from every folder in your email account.
POP3 poses a greater risk of device infection as it downloads all inbox messages to the local device. Comparatively, IMAP allows you to control which emails and attachments you open
POP3 misses an automatic backup system, meaning you can easily lose data. In contrast, IMAP allows you to re-retrieve any emails you haven't deleted
[9/30, 11:17 AM] Janani: The transport layer is known as the "heart" of the Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) model because it performs many important functions, including: 
 
Reliable data transfer
The transport layer ensures that data packets arrive accurately and reliably between the sender and receiver. 
 
Error checking
The transport layer performs error checking to ensure that the transmission is free of errors. 
 
Data segmentation
The transport layer breaks data from the session layer into segments for the network layer. 
 
Data reassembly
The transport layer reassembles the segments from the network layer and passes them on to the session layer. 
 
Flow control
The transport layer avoids sending more data than can be reliably transmitted. 
 
Addressing
The transport layer communicates with the correct application on the computer. 
 
Multiplexing
The transport layer ensures that any number of applications can use any number of network connections. 
 
The transport layer uses transmission protocols like the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) and User Datagram Protocol (UDP) to manage network traffic.
[9/30, 11:37 AM] Janani: A unique difference between a router and a gateway lies in their handling of protocols:

Router: A router forwards data within the same protocol (e.g., IPv4 to IPv4, IPv6 to IPv6). It decides the optimal path for data within networks using the same communication protocol.

Gateway: A gateway converts data between different protocols. For instance, it can translate between IPv4 and IPv6, or even between entirely different systems like TCP/IP and telephony protocols.


This protocol conversion capability is what sets gateways apart from routers in a unique way.
[10/9, 3:23 PM] Janani: Do I need a modem and a router?
A modem and router are both essential components of most home networks, especially for those who have a home office and work remotely. The modem is responsible for sending and receiving signals from the ISP, while the router disperses the signal to devices on the network.

In a typical home network setup, the modem is connected to the router, which is then connected to each device on the network. The modem and router are essential in ensuring a stable and reliable connection. Without a modem, the router would not be able to connect to the internet, and without a router, devices on the network would not be able to communicate
[10/19, 5:00 PM] Ruthika: What is CSMA protocol?

Problem approach
Carrier Sense Multiple Access (CSMA) is a network protocol for carriertransmission that operates in the Medium Access Control (MAC) layer. It senses or listens whether the shared channel for transmission is busy or not, and transmits if the channel is not busy. Using CMSA protocols, more than one users or nodes send and receive data through a shared medium that may be a single cable or optical fiber connecting multiple nodes, or a portion of the wireless spectrum.

Working Principle
When a station has frames to transmit, it attempts to detect presence of the carrier signal from the other nodes connected to the shared channel. If a carrier signal is detected, it implies that a transmission is in progress. The station waits till the ongoing transmission executes to completion, and then initiates its own transmission. Generally, transmissions by the node are received by all other nodes connected to the channel.
Since, the nodes detect for a transmission before sending their own frames,collision of frames is reduced. However, if two nodes detect an idle channel at the same time, they may simultaneously initiate transmission. This would cause the frames to garble resulting in a collision.
